{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-blog-post-js","path":"/cybernetics/week-8/","result":{"data":{"site":{"siteMetadata":{"title":"fridge notes"}},"markdownRemark":{"id":"d81350f1-2cdd-594c-85d9-6ae36adaf3bf","excerpt":"Readings podcast Towards an Anthropology of Women by Reina R. Reiter Response Tina Hold says sex work is a public health crisis — carrying condoms can be…","html":"<h2>Readings</h2>\n<p><a href=\"https://player.fm/series/why-are-people-into-that/sex-work-feminism-lecture-skidmore-college-317\">podcast</a></p>\n<p>Towards an Anthropology of Women by Reina R. Reiter</p>\n<h2>Response</h2>\n<p>Tina Hold says sex work is a public health crisis — carrying condoms can be evidence as participating in sex work. This intrigued me, and I checked the laws of New York State. As of 2013, it is now illegal to use contraception as evidence for sex work. </p>\n<p><a href=\"https://swp.urbanjustice.org/2019/09/21/new-york-state-assembly-bill-s1379-a2305-condom-bill/\">urban justice center article on sex work</a></p>\n<p>And this is the updated and maintained legislation as of 2021.</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://www.nysenate.gov/legislation/bills/2021/S4834\">current new york legislation</a></p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 590px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/blog/static/fe90121e9ce1bbdade63d9b689ae704f/29114/votes.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 56.08108108108109%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"votes\"\n        title=\"votes\"\n        src=\"/blog/static/fe90121e9ce1bbdade63d9b689ae704f/fcda8/votes.png\"\n        srcset=\"/blog/static/fe90121e9ce1bbdade63d9b689ae704f/12f09/votes.png 148w,\n/blog/static/fe90121e9ce1bbdade63d9b689ae704f/e4a3f/votes.png 295w,\n/blog/static/fe90121e9ce1bbdade63d9b689ae704f/fcda8/votes.png 590w,\n/blog/static/fe90121e9ce1bbdade63d9b689ae704f/efc66/votes.png 885w,\n/blog/static/fe90121e9ce1bbdade63d9b689ae704f/c83ae/votes.png 1180w,\n/blog/static/fe90121e9ce1bbdade63d9b689ae704f/29114/votes.png 1920w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p>One thing I find fascinating and sad is the amount of <code class=\"language-text\">Aye, with reservations</code>. <em>Four</em> legislators had RESERVATIONS about removing the use of contraception as evidence. Personally, I carry condoms and lube with me and I’m actively not a sex worker. What possible reservations could a legislator have other than being blatantly biased? </p>","frontmatter":{"title":"Week 8 - Sex Work","date":"November 08, 2021","description":"on sex work reading responses"}}},"pageContext":{"slug":"/cybernetics/week-8/","previous":{"fields":{"slug":"/biomaterials/week-2/"},"frontmatter":{"title":"Week 2 Assignments"}},"next":{"fields":{"slug":"/thesis/blog1/"},"frontmatter":{"title":"Ideation 1"}}}},"staticQueryHashes":["2841359383","3257411868"]}